In this article I cover how `chroot` can be
used to run `glibc` software on a `musl`-based system, modify
another Linux system without booting it, and create minimal environments for
development demonstrations.

## Requirements

All we will need is a Linux system with the basic Unix/Posix utilities. The section
on graphical applications assumes that your system is running a [Wayland][1] compositor (I
used [Sway][2]).

## Setting up a root directory

The `chroot` utility runs a command with the given directory set as the root `/`
directory of the filesystem. There are many use cases for such a tool, e.g.
to sandbox an application so that it cannot mess with files outside of its purview.

This article will not dwell on security concerns; we will assume that the
software we are running is not adversiarial. If secure sandboxing is your primary
interest, then further measures beyond `chroot` are necessary
to set up a true *container*, e.g.
[namespaces][3] and [cgroups][4] (see [this blog][5]). Containerization software such as [Docker][6]
manages all these aspects together.

[1]: https://wayland.freedesktop.org/
[2]: https://swaywm.org/
